			<div type="edition" xml:lang="san-Latn" rendition="class:83225 maturity:83211"><!--
This inscription is digitally edited by Dániel Balogh from photographs of the original stone (taken in Jhalawar Museum in January 2017), with reference to Fleet's CII (F) and Sircar's SI (S). Conjectural restorations were originally suggested by Fleet unless otherwise noted. Version of January 2019. Comments below are offered "as is" and do not represent a thoroughly researched or considered opinion.
--><lg n="1" met="vasantatilakā"><!--
Punctuation marks transcribed as double daṇḍas are double verticals with a hook at the top left of the first one. They seem to occur consistently at both half-verse and full-verse ends, though there doesn't appear to be one at the end of v1. (And the marks occur after every quarter of some longer verses at the end, v22 onward.) I supply identical punctuation at lost verse and half-verse ends.
-->
<l n="a"><lb
n="1"/><seg met="++-+---+--+-"><gap reason="lost" quantity="12" unit="character"/></seg> <unclear>ma</unclear>sya</l>
<l n="b">viṣṇor bbhujas sura-pati-dvi<unclear>pa</unclear>-has<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ta</supplied>-<unclear cert="low">dīrggha</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ḥ||</supplied></l><!--
L1. F (S following him) reads hasta-sarppa, showing only sa as unclear. He translates "the serpentine movement of the trunk" of Indra's elephant, which is a bit of a non sequitur. The subscript t and most of what F reads as sa are completely obliterated by a deep pit of the stone, P1010518. In the last character, subscript p is possible, but anything else is guesswork. I tentatively read dīrgghaḥ instead; the first lost character may have an i/ī mātrā, and the second one's main component resembles g, while the subscript component may be the left half of gh. Compare Harṣacarita 3, diṅnāga-hasta-dīrgho ... bāhur. Another possibility may be lamba (cf. lambi in v19).  S, but not F, restores a visarga after sarpa, which I think is necessary whatever the word; the half-verse would not have ended with an unfinished compound.
-->
