--></lg>
<lg n="14" met="vasantatilakā">
<l n="a">yāteṣu catu<unclear cert="low">r</unclear><unclear>ṣu</unclear> k<sic>ri</sic>teṣu śateṣu sau<choice><sic>s</sic><corr>m</corr></choice>y<unclear>e</unclear></l><!--
L19. F and S read sausyaiṣvāśīta, emending to saumyeṣv aśīta. Compare the date in the Bihar Kotra inscription of Naravarman (IN00018:2-3), caturṣu varṣa-śateṣu catu[#ḥ]saptateṣu [but that reading needs to be checked]. Also compare the Chhoti Sadri inscr, IN00203:15-16, yāteṣu paṁcasu śateṣv atha vatsarāṇāṁ dve vi{!ṅ!}śatī-samadhikeṣu sa-saptakeṣu. Fleet is aware that his emended reading is unmetrical. He considers the alternative reading sausyaiṣṭhāśīta and emendation to saumye 'ṣṭāśīta, but rejects this because he feels saumye should be in locative plural agreeing with śateṣu. I think it's OK to see it as in apposition to dine in the second half, though not very nice. Fleet (1888:73-74n1) further discusses the date and notes caturṣu is unmetrical but must be correct. He also considers and rejects other possibilities, such as reading yāteṣu ca tsapu, with tsapu being a possible "pronunciation value" assigned to the numeral 4; and interpreting kr̥teṣu as bhūtasaṁkhyā meaning 4, preceded by an unintelligible string. Since we now know that kr̥ta is the name of the era, we can almost be certain the word is used here in that sense, and the number of hundreds must be the preceding word.
--><!--
L19. In addition to the closeups, P1010493 and P1010494 also have good views of this section. For my reading ṣṭhāśīta, compare ṣvi a few characters later on in this line and ṣṭha in line 33 below: subscript v is more angular and its top is at the horizontal cenre; subscript ṭh is rounded and is attached at the top nearer the right-hand side. For my reading sye instead of syai, see the closeup photos. There are three strokes that may be vowel marks on this character on the basis of the rubbing. The one on the left, curving down, is definitely genuine. The one at the top, curving left, is very shallow and definitely not genuine. The one on the right seems to be slightly too large and crude, so I attribute it to damage.
--><!--
L19. See also the date of the Bihar Kotra stone IN00018 and cave (IN00224), probably ending with saptateṣu, as a possible parallel for this strange date. Stone: rājya-saṁvatsare caturṣu varṣa-śateṣu catu[+ḥ][#sa]ptateṣu śrāvaṇa-śukla-dvitīyāyāM. Cave: sva-rājya-saṁvatsare caturṣu var{!ś!}{=ṣ=}}a-śateṣu catu[+ḥ]saptateṣu phalgu{!ṇ!}a-māsa-bahula-pañcamyāṁ.
-->
