<l n="c"><unclear cert="low">tu</unclear>ṣṭām ivābharaṇa-jātibhir aṅganāṁ svāṁ</l><!--
L23. Fleet reads seṣṭām and emends to iṣṭām. Sircar reads śiṣṭām, which is a bit surprising semantically. Looking at photos of the stone, śi is impossible and se is extremely unlikely. I think the correct reading is tu; the right-hand side of the u mātrā is faint but visible to the left of the following subscript ṭ. Reading tuṣṭāṁ here also makes sense of sakala in the next quarter, which Fleet has to emend hard-handedly. (Admittedly, iva should be used enclitically, and in my reading it cannot be seen that way. Still, given the meagre skills of the poet, I think this is easily possible.)
-->
<l n="d">yo garggarā-taṭa-pura<unclear>ṁ</unclear> sa<unclear>ka</unclear>lañ-cakāra||</l><!--
