L24-25. V17cd is problematic. Fleet reads ś where I read g and emend to ś - the crossbar is definitely missing; compare gyā for śyā in l27 (there read as g by Fleet too). He otherwise reads as I do but emends/restores to śāstraiḥ stute ca vinaye vyavahāra-hīne yo 'pakṣapāta-rahito nidadhau sva-cintāM, translating "and who, (by nature) not free from partiality (for this particular virtue), has (always) applied (his) thoughts to courteous behaviour, destitute of litigation, which is applauded by the sacred writings". The readings are unclear in many places, but are nonetheless almost certain. However, Fleet's interpretation is tenuous, especially his translation of vyavahāra as litigation, understood in the context as "squabble". While vyavahāra does mean litigation, it does not mean squabble, which would be comparable to using 'procedure' in English as a synonym of squabble. I also find the phrase apakṣapāta-rahita unlikely. My own interpretation is also tenuous, also depends on emendation, and may be too modern, but I still believe it is more likely to be correct than Fleet's. I would translate,"Who administered his duties without partiality toward [a man] praised in the śāstras as well as [one] without education and a profession." I also think a pun is intended with pakṣmapāta (pakṣa does not seem to be attested in the sense of eyelash), so that this "eye" never blinks.
