L35. Though F (and, as usual, S) reads mātr̥ṇāñ, emending tr̥ to tr̥̄, I'm quite convinced there is an actual r̥̄ mātrā in the inscription here. P1010500 has a good view: we have the base character ta, and what looks like two subscript r-s (or r̥ marks), one more horizontal, the other steeper. (This contra Basham 1984:149 who explicitly notes that the short r̥ is a scribal error.)
--><!--
L36. Fleet restores pramudita, translating, "... Mothers, who utter loud and tremendous shouts in joy, (and) who stir up the (very) oceans with the mighty wind rising from the magic rites of their religion." Willis_2009:179 (probably following Lorenzen 2006) restores pracudita and translates, "An abode of the Mothers whose thunderous cries impel the rain clouds, and whose treasure - the waters - bursts forth with the mighty wind produced by their lyre." pracudita is attested in the MBh in a transitive sense, but I still find it awkward. Before the extant di, there is a character component that is indeed probably an u mātrā of the plain vertical type, so we are looking for a verbal root ending in ud, excluding rud and a few other possibilities. I think praṇudita may be a better choice, though in MW this participle is only attested in the sense of "beaten, struck" - but the verb pra-ṇud carries the primary meanings "to push on , propel , set in motion." Continuing this: if Basham is correct in interpreting ghana as cymbal/gong, which sounds like a very good idea, then praṇudita as "struck" is perfectly in place. And, now that we have a primary meaning for this, I'm actually beginning to like Willis's interpretation as a _secondary_, śliṣṭa meaning.
